                   <img alt="Composite banner of German and Dutch photograph albums © English Heritage Trust." src="/sites/default/files/composite_banner_eh88202653_eh88202652_web.jpg" style='cursor: default; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: sans-serif, Arial, Verdana, "Trebuchet MS"; font-size: 13px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); width: 850px; height: 266px;'/>

                 </p>
                 <p>

These unusual gifts from Germany and the Netherlands are made available online for the first time through a collaboration with

                  </a>
                  .

              <h3 class="campl-teaser-title">
               <a href="/1873-letters-go-online-158th-anniversary-origin">
                All Darwin's letters from 1873 go online for the anniversary of Origin
               </a>
              </h3>
              <span class="rdf-meta element-hidden" content="All Darwin's letters from 1873 go online for the anniversary of Origin" property="dc:title">
              </span>
              <span class="rdf-meta element-hidden" content="0" datatype="xsd:integer" property="sioc:num_replies">
              </span>
              <div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden">
               <div class="field-items">
                <div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded">
                 <p>
                  To celebrate the 158th anniversary of the publication of
                  <em>
                   Origin of species
                  </em>
                  on 24 November, the full transcripts and footnotes of over 500 letters from and to Charles Darwin in 1873 are now available online. Read about
                  <a href="https://www.darwinproject.ac.uk/letters/darwins-life-letters/darwins-letters-1873-animal-or-vegetable">
                   Darwin's life in 1873 through his letters
                  </a>
                  , or see
                  <a href="https://www.darwinproject.ac.uk/search?keyword=1873;sort=date;f1-date=1873">
                   a full list of his 1873 letters
                  </a>
                  . We have also added
                  <a href="https://www.darwinproject.ac.uk/fake-darwin">
                   a page debunking some common myths and misconceptions about Darwin's life and work
                  </a>
                  , where you can find out that Darwin did not introduce the term 'survival of the fittest' and he was not a stuffy father or an atheist.
                 </p>
                </div>
               </div>
